WEBVTT

1
00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:19.120
[birds chirping]

2
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
[clock ticking]

3
00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:27.440
[man grunts softly]

4
00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:34.000
[bottles rattling]

5
00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:46.440
[door shuts]

6
00:00:48.440 --> 00:00:49.920
[dog barks. whimpers]

7
00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:56.720
[man on radio] <i>…of his party.</i>

8
00:00:56.800 --> 00:00:59.920
<i>Mr. Heseltine says Britain
should reach for the levers of power</i>

9
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.280
<i>if only to prevent
others pulling them first.</i>

10
00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:06.680
<i>One dead in an Ulster gun battle
between soldiers and terrorists.</i>

11
00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:10.480
<i>Police make arrests over ballot rigging
in the transport union.</i>

12
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.160
<i>Confusion over plastic clingfilm…</i>

13
00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:14.120
Thank you. dear.

14
00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:16.960
<i>…government's cancer warning.
And animals to the slaughter.</i>

15
00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:20.760
<i>How the RSPCA hopes
to stop live animal exports.</i>

16
00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:24.880
<i>Michael Heseltine was speaking
to a conference in Hamburg.</i>

17
00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:27.680
<i>Mr. Heseltine is now
on his way back to London</i>

18
00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.480
<i>to be in the Commons this afternoon.</i>

19
00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:32.640
<i>There. Sir Geoffrey Howe
is expected to spell out in detail</i>

20
00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:34.600
<i>the reasons for his resignation.</i>

21
00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.120
<i>Is there anything
Sir Geoffrey is likely to say</i>

22
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:40.640
<i>that could influence Mr. Heseltine
on whether to throw his hat in the ring?</i>

23
00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:43.320
[man 2] <i>Well.
Sir Geoffrey is an extremely cautious man.</i>

24
00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:46.760
<i>I suspect
that his speech will be carefully written.</i>

25
00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:50.080
<i>and I just wonder
whether it will be sufficiently in code</i>

26
00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.320
<i>not really to damage the prime minister.</i>

27
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.560
<i>Sir Geoffrey has very deep personal
and ideological differences</i>

28
00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.160
<i>with the prime minister.
I think he will spell them out.</i>

29
00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:02.360
<i>but whether he will spell them out
in clear. set terms</i>

30
00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.520
<i>that amount to an assault
on her leadership.</i>

31
00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:06.480
<i>I think we have to wait and see for that.</i>

32
00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:10.200
[Speaker] <i>I remind the House
that a resignation statement</i>

33
00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:13.680
<i>is heard in silence
and without interruption.</i>

34
00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.640
Sir Geoffrey Howe.

35
00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:19.040
[MPs] Hear. hear.

36
00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:22.200
Mr. Speaker. sir.

37
00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:27.040
"I find. to my astonishment.
that a quarter of a century has passed

38
00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:29.960
since I last spoke
from one of these backbenches."

39
00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:30.960
[murmuring]

40
00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:34.240
"Mr. Speaker. I believe
that both the chancellor and the governor

41
00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:36.200
are cricketing enthusiasts."

42
00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:39.680
"So I hope that there is
no monopoly of cricketing metaphors."

43
00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:42.800
"Increasingly.
those of us close to the prime minister

44
00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:45.400
feel like opening batsmen
being sent to the crease.

45
00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:48.120
only to find
the moment the first balls are bowled

46
00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:52.600
that our bats have been broken
before the game by the team captain."

47
00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:54.640
[laughter]

48
00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:55.720
[tapping]

49
00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:56.880
[Speaker] Order!

50
00:02:57.840 --> 00:02:58.840
Order.

51
00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:01.960
"The point… The point. Mr. Speaker.

52
00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:05.120
was perhaps more sharply put
by a British businessman.

53
00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.760
trading in Brussels and elsewhere.
who wrote to me last week."

54
00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:12.120
'People throughout Europe. ' he said.

55
00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:15.040
'see our prime minister's finger-wagging

56
00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:20.320
and hear her passionate 'No. no. no'

57
00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:25.560
much more clearly than the content
of the carefully worded formal texts.'"

58
00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:27.840
"'It is too easy. ' he went on.

59
00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:30.920
'for them to believe
that we all share her attitudes.'"

60
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.760
"'For why else. ' he asked.

61
00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:36.080
'has she been our prime minister
for so long?'"

62
00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:37.880
[murmuring]

63
00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:40.160
[Howe] "'This is. '
my correspondent concluded.

64
00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:43.360
'a desperately serious situation
for our country.'"

65
00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:47.200
And sadly. Mr. Speaker. I have to agree.

66
00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:50.000
"The conflict of loyalty.

67
00:03:50.840 --> 00:03:53.960
of loyalty to my right honorable friend
the prime minister.

68
00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:57.480
and. after all. in two decades together.

69
00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:01.600
that instinct of loyalty
is still very real…

70
00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:06.360
and of loyalty to what I perceive to be
the true interests of the nation.

71
00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:10.680
that conflict of loyalty
has become all too great."

72
00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:13.360
"I no longer believe it possible

73
00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.480
to resolve that conflict
from within this government."

74
00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:18.320
"That is why I have resigned."

75
00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:21.560
"In doing so.
I have done what I believe to be right

76
00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:23.840
for my party and my country."

77
00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.320
"The time has come for others
to consider their own response

78
00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:30.560
to the tragic conflict of loyalties

79
00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:34.960
with which I have myself wrestled…
for perhaps too long."

80
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:37.880
[MPs. scattered] Hear. hear.

81
00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:39.760
Lilibet?

82
00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:45.560
[vacuum whirring]

83
00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:52.520
- Uh. the Queen?
- In the drawing room. Your Royal Highness.

84
00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:53.600
Right.

85
00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:57.640
She has resumed
her affair with Major Hewitt

86
00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:02.160
with flagrant disregard for the agreement
we made in our meeting with you.

87
00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:05.800
A meeting in which it is now clear
she brazenly lied to your face.

88
00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:09.480
So I hope you agree

89
00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:12.120
it leaves me no option
but to start a formal separation.

90
00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:13.200
Oh. Charles!

91
00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:15.576
I'm wretchedly unhappy.
yet there is someone else out there

92
00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:17.280
who would make me perfectly happy.

93
00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:19.160
- Quick. switch on the television.
- Why?

94
00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:21.240
It's the Ides of March.

95
00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:25.080
It's Julius Caesar.
or should I say <i>Julia </i>Caesar?

96
00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:27.360
We're in the middle
of an important conversation.

97
00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:29.040
- Shh.
- [man] <i>…her style of government.</i>

98
00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:33.840
<i>He says her nightmare image of Europe
risks the future of the nation.</i>

99
00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:35.720
<i>Can Sir Geoffrey's peroration.</i>

100
00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:39.160
<i>where he said the time has come
for others to consider their response.</i>

101
00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:43.160
<i>be read in any other way
than a clear invitation to open a contest</i>

102
00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:44.120
<i>for the leadership?</i>

103
00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:47.440
[man 2] <i>That is one of the implications.
Some people would go further than that.</i>

104
00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.480
<i>They would say he is urging people
to vote against Mrs. Thatcher…</i>

105
00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:52.600
[woman] <i>…Thatcher is facing
the most serious threat</i>

106
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:53.800
<i>to her 11 years in power…</i>

107
00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.160
[man 3] <i>…first time in 15 years…</i>

108
00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.880
[man 4] <i>Geoffrey Howe.
Mrs. Thatcher's longest-serving colleague</i>

109
00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:01.520
<i>throughout her years in power.
turned on her in the Commons today</i>

110
00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:04.440
<i>and accused her
of risking the nation's future.</i>

111
00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:06.760
- [phone ringing]
- <i>He was explaining for the first time</i>

112
00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:09.840
<i>why he resigned as deputy prime minister
12 days ago.</i>

113
00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.320
[man 5] <i>…refusal to keep in step
with the European community.</i>

114
00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:14.120
[man 4] <i>…a coded diplomatic speech.</i>

115
00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:16.720
<i>Instead.
years of resentment and frustration</i>

116
00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:19.640
<i>were compressed
into a bitter attack on Mrs. Thatcher</i>

117
00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.400
<i>and her attitude to Europe.</i>

118
00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:23.120
<i>He called on Conservative MPs</i>

119
00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.360
<i>to consider what he described
as their conflict of loyalties…</i>

120
00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:28.400
[man 6] <i>Howe delivered
a stinging indictment…</i>

121
00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:31.200
[man 2] <i>There is great bitterness
on the prime minister's side.</i>

122
00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:35.080
<i>and they hope there will be some reaction
in her favor. It's down to Conservative…</i>

123
00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:37.480
[man 7] <i>Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
faces a challenge</i>

124
00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:39.040
<i>that could cost her her job.</i>

125
00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:42.320
[man 8] <i>…MPs. ministers. and peers
are still trying to assess</i>

126
00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:45.280
<i>what one described
as an incitement to mutiny</i>

127
00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:48.000
<i>and another said was an act of treachery.</i>

128
00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:50.080
[stifling sobs]

129
00:06:56.200 --> 00:06:58.200
[theme music plays]

130
00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.040
[somber music playing]

131
00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[turn signal blinking]

132
00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:51.640
[car door shuts]

133
00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:53.680
[engine turns over]

134
00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:14.440
[whistle blows]

135
00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:15.680
[overlapping grunts]

136
00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:17.760
[boy] William!

137
00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:19.760
Run!

138
00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:21.800
Oh. Ivo's got it! Ivo's got it!

139
00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:23.560
Go. Ivo! Go. Ivo!

140
00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:24.640
- Ivo!
- Move it!

141
00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:27.960
- Yes. well done!
- [whistle blows]

142
00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:29.040
Yes. well done!

143
00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:31.880
Well done. Ivo!

144
00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:34.240
Oh. he's brilliant. isn't he? Yes!

145
00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:35.840
[cheering]

146
00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:38.120
Did you see that? Yes!

147
00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:39.600
Well done. boys!

148
00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.800
Bye. my darling.
Not long until the holidays.

149
00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:43.880
Hmm?

150
00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:46.760
- Love you.
- [camera shutters clicking]

151
00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:50.960
- Well done today.
- Thank you.

152
00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:52.480
And we'll see you at Christmas.

153
00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:54.480
Goodbye.

154
00:09:56.920 --> 00:09:57.920
Take care.

155
00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:02.840
[car doors shut]

156
00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:16.120
Is that it?

157
00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:18.760
We're not going to talk again. ever?

158
00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:21.440
Since every time we do talk.
it ends in an argument.

159
00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:23.520
I'd say silence was preferable.

160
00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:31.000
What's this I hear
about a trip to New York?

161
00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:32.960
Oh. don't look so surprised.

162
00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:35.480
The government requested it.
Everyone knows I'm going.

163
00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:37.440
No one knew you were going on your own.

164
00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.280
What an ugly. avaricious piece
of self-advancement that is.

165
00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:44.240
[Diana] I'd sooner be doing it
with my husband by my side.

166
00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:45.960
[scoffs] Doing what?

167
00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:49.800
The past few months. you've barely been
in a fit state psychologically

168
00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:52.440
to go to the hairdresser.
much less represent the Crown.

169
00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:56.720
Although I gather you still found time
to see… certain other people.

170
00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:02.720
I think
this conversation's gone as far as it can.

171
00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:05.240
You were the one who insisted on talking.

172
00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:08.440
I always said silence was preferable.

173
00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:14.640
- [man] Mrs. Thatcher?
- [woman] Prime Minister?

174
00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:18.960
[Thatcher] <i>One crisis rising above
all the others today. Your Majesty.</i>

175
00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:19.880
Yes.

176
00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:23.240
An inconvenience
one would dearly like to avoid.

177
00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:27.080
given the significant challenges
this country already faces.

178
00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:30.040
The crisis in the Gulf.

179
00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:32.360
Oh. <i>that </i>crisis?

180
00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:35.280
Well. that is
the predominant challenge facing us.

181
00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:38.360
I thought you might be
referring to matters closer to home.

182
00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:41.080
There are one or two
minor domestic matters.

183
00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:44.520
some changes
to the fishing license conditions.

184
00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:48.400
but nothing I would want
to waste your valuable time with.

185
00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:51.960
You don't think
we should briefly discuss… that speech?

186
00:11:52.040 --> 00:11:53.440
Which speech?

187
00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.880
The resignation speech
made by Sir Geoffrey Howe

188
00:11:56.960 --> 00:11:58.280
that's caused such a stir.

189
00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:00.360
Why would we want to discuss that?

190
00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:02.960
Because a great deal of fuss
is being made of it.

191
00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:04.320
[Thatcher] Oh. poor Geoffrey.

192
00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.400
I'd offered him
the position of deputy prime minister.

193
00:12:07.480 --> 00:12:10.720
and he seems to have taken it
rather the wrong way.

194
00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:14.560
In the newspapers. his speech is seen
as a direct challenge to your authority.

195
00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.560
I think that all depends
on which newspapers you're reading.

196
00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:20.880
Not just newspapers. Television too.

197
00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:21.960
Or watching.

198
00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.600
And as sovereign. I must ask you…

199
00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.400
do you expect a leadership challenge?

200
00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:32.160
- The prime minister came to see me today.
- [Philip] Ah. yes.

201
00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:34.560
[Elizabeth]To discuss
the crisis in the Gulf.

202
00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:35.640
What?

203
00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:38.920
Not the fact
that she'd just been knifed in the back

204
00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.840
by one of her longest-standing allies?

205
00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:42.360
No. I asked her about that.

206
00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.480
- Did you really?
- Yes.

207
00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:46.360
You're brave.

208
00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:48.720
- [chuckles softly]
- [Philip] What did she say?

209
00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:50.760
She said the situation was unfortunate…

210
00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:56.240
…but it amounts to little more
than petty rivalries and resentments…

211
00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:57.936
…played out
at the level of the schoolyard.

212
00:12:57.960 --> 00:13:00.840
I shall see them off in no time.

213
00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:06.680
And. really.
we should not dignify an insignificant…

214
00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:10.000
[mockingly] …internal party squabble
with any more of our precious time.

215
00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:13.280
[silverware clattering]

216
00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:16.880
Well… [scoffs]

217
00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:20.440
[clock ticking]

218
00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:29.600
[man] <i>Sir Geoffrey's attack makes this.
the criticism of Mrs. Thatcher.</i>

219
00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:31.200
<i>much more lethal.</i>

220
00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:33.120
<i>I think she's in deep trouble.</i>

221
00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:37.280
<i>not that she will be beaten
in the first ballot by Michael Heseltine.</i>

222
00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:40.480
<i>but more probably that
there will be enough votes against her</i>

223
00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:44.080
<i>and enough abstentions
to damage her seriously.</i>

224
00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:47.040
<i>One person said to me
that he thought it possible.</i>

225
00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:48.640
<i>if she were badly enough damaged.</i>

226
00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:51.440
<i>that members of the Cabinet
would go to the chief whip</i>

227
00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:53.840
<i>and say that
she ought to consider her future.</i>

228
00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:55.920
<i>It's premature to say that yet.</i>

229
00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.920
<i>but undoubtedly
there's a rather stronger tide</i>

230
00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.600
<i>running against Mrs. Thatcher tonight
than there has ever been before.</i>

231
00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:03.680
[phone rings]

232
00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:06.080
Powell.

233
00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:07.840
Yes.

234
00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:09.560
Yeah.

235
00:14:11.240 --> 00:14:12.240
I see.

236
00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:15.080
Thank you.

237
00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:16.680
[hangs up receiver]

238
00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:18.880
How many?

239
00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:21.000
- We're four short.
- [Thatcher] Oh.

240
00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:23.400
Not enough to stop it
going to a second ballot.

241
00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:27.960
Oh. it's betrayal of the very worst kind.

242
00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:30.800
[sighs]

243
00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.480
They owe their political lives to me.

244
00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:36.120
- It's despicable.
- Oh. those little men!

245
00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:40.960
And you want me
to get on my knees to them?

246
00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:43.600
Never.

247
00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:49.200
Have them brought in to me.

248
00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:52.480
One by one.

249
00:14:53.160 --> 00:14:55.160
[overlapping chatter]

250
00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:16.240
First item on the agenda
is Her Royal Highness's forthcoming…

251
00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:19.200
<i>solo </i>visit to New York.

252
00:15:19.720 --> 00:15:21.440
Looking at the itinerary.

253
00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.560
our concern would be
that it seems to be challenging.

254
00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:28.760
Several appointments each day.

255
00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:31.520
- It's just four days. Edward.
- In multiple locations.

256
00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:36.200
We all know the toll
a schedule of engagements can take.

257
00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:41.160
and I'm sure no one here would wish to see
the Princess of Wales overstretched.

258
00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:43.920
Certainly not at a risk to her own health.

259
00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.520
The Princess of Wales's health
is exemplary.

260
00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:47.960
Mental health.

261
00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.600
Not to mention the amount of time
she'd be separated from her children

262
00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:56.160
and the distress that might cause her.

263
00:15:56.240 --> 00:15:59.800
The Princess of Wales
is well aware of what's required of her

264
00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.360
and is very much
looking forward to the trip.

265
00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:10.560
[reporters chattering]

266
00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:23.560
I have only one question.

267
00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:27.760
Will you support me?

268
00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:30.760
Of course.

269
00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:34.120
You will always have
my unconditional support.

270
00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:35.440
I am with you.

271
00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:36.760
You can always count on me.

272
00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:40.280
The problem is…

273
00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:42.600
…the numbers are against you…

274
00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:45.920
[man 4] …and your inability
to unite the party behind you…

275
00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:46.880
…over Europe…

276
00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:48.040
…over the economy…

277
00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:49.000
…over taxation…

278
00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:52.120
[man 3] Perhaps if your methods
were less confrontational…

279
00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:55.800
…and if you'd consulted with Cabinet
rather than ruling by decree…

280
00:16:55.880 --> 00:16:59.280
…your rejection
of core Conservative values.

281
00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:00.480
of moderation…

282
00:17:00.560 --> 00:17:01.640
…compassion…

283
00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:04.040
…and your total disregard
for the center ground…

284
00:17:04.120 --> 00:17:05.600
[man 6] …leaves you vulnerable.

285
00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:08.240
[man 3] Exposed. Isolated.

286
00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:11.680
I shall always defend you. Margaret.

287
00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:13.320
<i>Always.</i>

288
00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:15.000
But…

289
00:17:15.080 --> 00:17:16.320
…as your friend…

290
00:17:17.120 --> 00:17:18.400
…as an ally…

291
00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:20.760
…I think I speak for the majority
when I say…

292
00:17:20.840 --> 00:17:24.480
[man 1] …the time might have come
for some new blood.

293
00:17:26.440 --> 00:17:29.320
[man 2] <i>…and that it would be
in everyone's best interests</i>

294
00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:32.360
<i>if you were to… stand down.</i>

295
00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:39.600
[door shuts]

296
00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:49.160
Bastards.

297
00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:53.120
The bloody lot of them.

298
00:17:54.360 --> 00:17:55.360
Murderers.

299
00:17:55.960 --> 00:17:57.120
[inhales deeply]

300
00:17:58.760 --> 00:17:59.960
[Denis scoffs]

301
00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:03.040
[Denis sniffles]

302
00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:05.120
So… [clears throat]

303
00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:06.240
…is that it?

304
00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:08.640
Is that the end?

305
00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:11.040
No.

306
00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:14.760
I still have one card to play.

307
00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:18.320
[man on radio]
<i>Britain will send more troops to the Gulf.</i>

308
00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:20.760
<i>The defence secretary Tom King
has said Britain…</i>

309
00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:24.480
[Thatcher] <i>President Bush called
to tell me he thought it barbaric.</i>

310
00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.280
<i>Chancellor Kohl said it was inhumane.</i>

311
00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:32.240
<i>Mikhail Gorbachev reminded me
that ten years ago.</i>

312
00:18:32.320 --> 00:18:35.920
<i>it was Britain
holding democratic elections</i>

313
00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.280
<i>whilst Russia staged cabinet coups.</i>

314
00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:41.040
<i>Now it's the other way round.</i>

315
00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:43.600
What they all agree on

316
00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:48.960
is that getting rid of me
is an act of national self-harm.

317
00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:51.120
which is why I've come to you. ma'am.

318
00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:55.880
that together we may act
in the national self-interest.

319
00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:57.000
How might I help?

320
00:18:57.760 --> 00:18:59.960
[Thatcher] By dissolving Parliament.

321
00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:02.800
What?

322
00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:05.960
We are on the brink of war.

323
00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:10.280
What kind of signal
does that give to our enemies.

324
00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:11.600
to Saddam.

325
00:19:11.680 --> 00:19:14.720
if we were to change leadership now?

326
00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:18.120
It would make us look
hopelessly weak and divided.

327
00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:19.800
I agree it's not ideal.

328
00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:22.600
Have you consulted Cabinet on this matter?

329
00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:24.560
I have not. ma'am.

330
00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:27.160
Surely that would be
the normal course of action?

331
00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:29.200
With all due respect.

332
00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:32.200
the decision to dissolve Parliament

333
00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:35.600
is in the gift
of the prime minister alone.

334
00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:40.320
It is entirely within my power
to do this if I see fit.

335
00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:41.480
You are correct.

336
00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.520
Technically.
it is within your power to request this.

337
00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:48.240
But we must all ask ourselves

338
00:19:48.760 --> 00:19:52.080
when to exercise those things
that are within our power and when not to.

339
00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:56.680
Your first instinct as a person.
I think. is often to act.

340
00:19:57.280 --> 00:19:58.880
To exercise power.

341
00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:01.240
Well.
that is what people want in a leader.

342
00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:05.240
To show conviction and strength.

343
00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:06.600
To <i>lead.</i>

344
00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:10.640
I'm merely asking the question.

345
00:20:11.240 --> 00:20:15.720
Whether it is correct to exercise a power
simply because it is yours to use.

346
00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:19.960
Power is nothing without authority.

347
00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:22.200
And at this moment.

348
00:20:23.320 --> 00:20:24.960
your Cabinet is against you.

349
00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:27.480
Your party is against you.

350
00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.640
And if the polls are to be believed.

351
00:20:29.720 --> 00:20:31.800
if you were
to call a general election today.

352
00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:33.000
you would not win.

353
00:20:33.520 --> 00:20:36.320
Which suggests the country is against you.

354
00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:40.000
Perhaps the time has come

355
00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:42.960
for you to try doing nothing for once.

356
00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:46.280
The difference is…

357
00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:49.320
you have power…

358
00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:51.520
in doing nothing.

359
00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:54.080
I…

360
00:20:54.920 --> 00:20:56.320
will have nothing.

361
00:20:58.200 --> 00:20:59.720
You will have your dignity.

362
00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:03.400
There is no dignity in the wilderness.

363
00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:05.720
Then might I suggest
you don't think of it as that.

364
00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:10.160
Think of it as an opportunity
to pursue other passions.

365
00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:13.240
I have other loves.

366
00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:17.440
My husband. my children…

367
00:21:18.720 --> 00:21:23.640
But this job <i>is </i>my only true passion.

368
00:21:25.520 --> 00:21:27.720
And to have it taken from me…

369
00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:32.000
stolen from me so cruelly…

370
00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:36.480
What hurts the most

371
00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:40.320
is that we had come so far.

372
00:21:41.880 --> 00:21:46.240
And now to have
the opportunity to finish the job

373
00:21:46.320 --> 00:21:49.520
snatched away at the very last…

374
00:21:59.240 --> 00:22:01.240
[indistinct announcement]

375
00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:11.240
[Diana yells] <i>I'm in hell!</i>

376
00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:13.160
And he just hates me.

377
00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:15.720
And wants me to fail.

378
00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:18.560
He tells everyone I'm mad.

379
00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:23.080
They treat me like I'm mad.

380
00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:25.720
And I'm starting to <i>feel </i>mad.

381
00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:28.480
Why did I agree to this trip?

382
00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:31.280
<i>I'm going to fall flat on my face.</i>

383
00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:38.600
[engines roaring]

384
00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:46.120
[crowd cheering. chattering]

385
00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:51.120
All right?

386
00:22:51.480 --> 00:22:52.480
I think so.

387
00:22:58.120 --> 00:23:00.360
- [speaks indistinctly]
- Lovely to meet you. Hello.

388
00:23:01.640 --> 00:23:02.680
Lovely to meet you.

389
00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:05.840
[reporter 1] Princess Diana. one quick…

390
00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:07.480
[overlapping chatter]

391
00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:09.560
[reporter 2] Over here. please. Lady Di!

392
00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:23.160
[theme from <i>New York. New York</i> playing]

393
00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:34.840
[chattering]

394
00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:14.000
[music ends]

395
00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:16.520
- [water running]
- [retching. coughing]

396
00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:19.760
[retching continues]

397
00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:28.200
[toilet flushes]

398
00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:52.560
[light traffic noises outside]

399
00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:09.800
- [sirens whooping]
- [horns honking]

400
00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:15.760
[man] I love you. Diana!

401
00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:17.360
[woman] Diana! Diana!

402
00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:30.120
- [hip-hop music playing]
- [cheering]

403
00:25:47.600 --> 00:25:49.600
[crowd cheering]

404
00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:04.360
Thank you so much.
That's so kind. Thank you.

405
00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:05.720
- Your Royal Highness.
- Hello.

406
00:26:07.320 --> 00:26:09.040
We're so thrilled to have you with us.

407
00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:12.160
This is Linda Correa.

408
00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:13.440
Lovely to meet you. miss.

409
00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:16.960
They told us there was a waiting list
for public housing…

410
00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:19.560
[reporter] A modest hospital
on the wrong side of Harlem

411
00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:22.720
very few American politicians
have ever even thought to visit.

412
00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:24.560
but today this is the final stop

413
00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:27.520
on Princess Diana's
whirlwind tour of New York.

414
00:26:32.840 --> 00:26:34.000
Your Royal Highness.

415
00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:44.840
[doctor] <i>We established
the pediatric AIDS unit two years ago</i>

416
00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:48.880
<i>to deal with the rising problem
of infants suffering with the disease.</i>

417
00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:50.960
[babies crying]

418
00:26:58.560 --> 00:26:59.560
Hello.

419
00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:04.720
Many of the children had been abandoned

420
00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:08.000
or have parents who are addicts
or sick with the virus.

421
00:27:08.080 --> 00:27:12.120
They desperately need foster parents.
but people are too afraid to take them.

422
00:27:12.200 --> 00:27:13.200
Why?

423
00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:17.520
Because of the stigma.
The fear of the disease.

424
00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:28.840
[people gasping softly. murmuring]

425
00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:37.360
[reporter] <i>Chants of
"We want the princess" were heard</i>

426
00:27:37.440 --> 00:27:39.400
<i>in New York's Harlem neighborhood today.</i>

427
00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:40.800
<i>A triumphant end to a trip</i>

428
00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:43.440
<i>which has seen the princess fly solo
for the first time.</i>

429
00:27:43.520 --> 00:27:47.200
<i>hitting new heights
without her husband. Prince Charles.</i>

430
00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:50.800
<i>We love her. She's beautiful. She's warm.</i>

431
00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:53.960
<i>She's perfect. They don't want her there.
we would love to have her here.</i>

432
00:27:54.680 --> 00:27:58.360
[woman] <i>The way she hugged that boy
in the hospital nearly broke my heart.</i>

433
00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:00.640
[man 1] <i>Prince Charles is a lucky man.</i>

434
00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:04.080
[man 2]<i> Princess Di. thank you
for bringing love and vitality</i>

435
00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:05.880
<i>- to the Lower East Side!
- </i>[cheering]

436
00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:08.400
<i>She knows how to make people feel good.</i>

437
00:28:08.480 --> 00:28:11.000
<i>and that is a God-given talent.
Am I right?</i>

438
00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:12.120
[woman] <i>Yeah!</i>

439
00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:14.200
[cheers fading out]

440
00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:16.280
[clock ticking]

441
00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:24.880
[thunder rumbling]

442
00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:29.920
[Camilla] <i>If you care about me as much
as you say you do. sir. you will let go</i>

443
00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
<i>of these ideas
of breaking it off with Diana.</i>

444
00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:33.880
Why?

445
00:28:34.960 --> 00:28:36.720
Don't you want us to be free. to…

446
00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:39.000
live our life in the open?

447
00:28:40.400 --> 00:28:41.280
I do.

448
00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:43.280
[sighs deeply]

449
00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:48.120
But I want to be humiliated
and attacked even less.

450
00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:52.640
That's what'll happen if you put me
in a popularity contest against her.

451
00:28:53.360 --> 00:28:54.240
I <i>will </i>lose.

452
00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:56.080
- Oh…
<i>- </i>[Camilla] I'm an old woman.

453
00:28:56.680 --> 00:28:58.320
I'm a married woman.

454
00:28:58.400 --> 00:29:01.080
Nowhere near as pretty.
nowhere near as radiant.

455
00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:05.120
Someone who looks like me
has no place in a fairy tale.

456
00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:08.360
That's all people want. is a fairy tale.

457
00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:11.080
If they knew the truth
about our feelings for one another.

458
00:29:11.160 --> 00:29:12.440
they'd have their fairy tale.

459
00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:13.520
[Camilla] No!

460
00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.440
To be the protagonist of a fairy tale.
you must first be wronged.

461
00:29:18.040 --> 00:29:19.040
A victim.

462
00:29:20.920 --> 00:29:23.320
Which. if we were to become public.
we would make her.

463
00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:27.920
In the narrative laws
of fairy tales versus reality…

464
00:29:28.960 --> 00:29:30.840
the fairy tale always prevails.

465
00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:35.840
She will… always defeat me
in the court of public opinion.

466
00:29:35.920 --> 00:29:37.560
What is all this. my darling?

467
00:29:39.080 --> 00:29:40.640
What's got into you today?

468
00:29:44.800 --> 00:29:46.000
[Camilla] It's reality. sir.

469
00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:50.120
She's the Princess of Wales.

470
00:29:51.360 --> 00:29:54.280
She's a future queen.
the mother to a future king.

471
00:29:56.440 --> 00:29:59.200
- And I'm just...
- My one… true love.

472
00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:04.960
A mistress.

473
00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:10.520
Mistress to the Prince of Wales. just like
my great-grandmother Alice Keppel

474
00:30:10.600 --> 00:30:14.680
was the mistress to the Prince of Wales.
your great-great-grandfather.

475
00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:16.560
And he loved her till the end.

476
00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:27.560
Leave this with me.

477
00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:37.160
[newsman] <i>Number 10 is a house
and a home as well as an office.</i>

478
00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:39.400
<i>and as Margaret Thatcher left it
after so long.</i>

479
00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:40.960
<i>there was applause to be heard.</i>

480
00:30:41.040 --> 00:30:44.160
<i>and. I'm told. a tear or two shed
among the unseen staff.</i>

481
00:30:44.240 --> 00:30:47.200
<i>Mrs. Thatcher's own voice
had an emotional edge to it.</i>

482
00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:49.080
<i>Ladies and gentlemen.</i>

483
00:30:49.640 --> 00:30:54.080
<i>we are leaving Downing Street
for the last time</i>

484
00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:58.680
<i>after 11 and a half wonderful years.</i>

485
00:30:58.760 --> 00:31:01.880
[newswoman] <i>It was the end of an era
dominated by this woman</i>

486
00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:04.600
<i>whose name has become a political byword.</i>

487
00:31:04.680 --> 00:31:06.400
<i>Eleven years of Thatcherism.</i>

488
00:31:06.920 --> 00:31:09.480
[newsman]
<i>She recovered quickly for one last wave.</i>

489
00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:13.760
<i>But then
the Iron Lady's composure almost broke.</i>

490
00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:16.080
<i>Watch her face as she reaches her car.</i>

491
00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:27.800
<i>Friends say that she is deeply shocked
by the seeming injustice of it all.</i>

492
00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:29.160
<i>Three election victories</i>

493
00:31:29.240 --> 00:31:32.360
<i>and a clear. though insufficient.
majority in the first ballot</i>

494
00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.800
<i>rewarded. as she sees it. with the sack.</i>

495
00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:38.240
<i>Mrs. Thatcher. of course.
has a new home now in Dulwich…</i>

496
00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:40.320
Martin? Could you ask the prime...

497
00:31:40.400 --> 00:31:43.000
Could you ask Mrs. Thatcher
to come and see me?

498
00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:06.600
When I ascended the throne…

499
00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:08.800
I was just a girl.

500
00:32:09.480 --> 00:32:10.880
Twenty-five years old.

501
00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:13.160
And I was surrounded

502
00:32:13.240 --> 00:32:16.320
by stuffy. rather patronizing
gray-haired men everywhere

503
00:32:16.400 --> 00:32:17.760
telling me what to do.

504
00:32:19.680 --> 00:32:20.960
And I wanted to say…

505
00:32:22.440 --> 00:32:26.880
the way you dealt with all your stuffy.
rather patronizing gray-haired men

506
00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:28.680
throughout your time in office

507
00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:30.320
and saw them all off…

508
00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:32.240
Well. they've had their revenge now.

509
00:32:35.120 --> 00:32:38.920
I was shocked by the way
in which you were forced to leave office.

510
00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:42.440
And I wanted to offer my sympathy.

511
00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:45.840
Not just as Queen to prime minister…

512
00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:48.680
but woman to woman.

513
00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:52.200
Throughout the time we worked together.

514
00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:55.000
people tended to focus
on our many differences.

515
00:32:57.320 --> 00:33:00.200
Which was lazy and misleading. I think.

516
00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:04.200
And overlooked the many things
we do have in common.

517
00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:06.560
Our generation.

518
00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:08.840
Our Christianity.

519
00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:10.520
Our work ethic.

520
00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:12.520
Our sense of duty.

521
00:33:14.760 --> 00:33:15.760
But above all…

522
00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:19.400
our devotion to this country
that we both love.

523
00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:23.160
So with that in mind…

524
00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:38.760
The Order of Merit…

525
00:33:39.720 --> 00:33:42.200
is not awarded by some faceless committee.

526
00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:46.160
It comes at the personal discretion
of the sovereign

527
00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:50.920
and is in recognition
of exceptionally meritorious service.

528
00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:54.920
It is limited to just 24 recipients.

529
00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:57.120
no matter their background.

530
00:33:58.320 --> 00:34:00.200
You could be the daughter of a duke.

531
00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:02.440
Or a greengrocer.

532
00:34:05.840 --> 00:34:08.600
What matters… is your accomplishments.

533
00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:11.240
And nobody can deny…

534
00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:15.200
that this is a very different country now

535
00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.480
to the one inherited
by our first woman prime minister.

536
00:34:23.920 --> 00:34:26.280
Now. it's normally handed over in the box.

537
00:34:29.160 --> 00:34:30.720
But if you would allow me…

538
00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:47.040
Congratulations.

539
00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:09.720
[handbag rattles]

540
00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:19.760
[doors open]

541
00:35:27.840 --> 00:35:29.000
[doors shut]

542
00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:37.440
[classical music plays loudly inside car]

543
00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:53.840
[inhales]

544
00:35:53.920 --> 00:35:55.200
[exhales]

545
00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:05.080
[doors open]

546
00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:14.440
It's kind of you to come.

547
00:36:15.160 --> 00:36:16.600
Why would you say that?

548
00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:18.760
I think
even my sternest critics would concede

549
00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:21.480
that my first solo trip
has not been a disaster.

550
00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:23.760
that I didn't fall
totally flat on my face.

551
00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:28.080
So I can only imagine. hope.
that you've come here to apologize.

552
00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:29.600
to eat your words.

553
00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:31.520
and congratulate me.

554
00:36:33.880 --> 00:36:37.080
Your… capacity for self-delusion…

555
00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:39.360
never ceases to amaze me.

556
00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:43.280
We're all glad
you're back where you belong

557
00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:46.840
without too much damage done.
You have two sons that need you.

558
00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:50.200
Our sons have easily survived
me being away four days.

559
00:36:50.280 --> 00:36:52.760
I'm not sure
one can say the same for the rest of us.

560
00:36:56.040 --> 00:36:59.640
The exquisite selfishness of your motives

561
00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:00.720
and the…

562
00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:05.480
the <i>calculated </i>vulgarity of the antics…

563
00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.440
knowing full well
the headlines they would get.

564
00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:10.640
"Antics"?

565
00:37:10.720 --> 00:37:12.360
Grandstanding like that.

566
00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:15.680
You think we couldn't do that too?

567
00:37:15.760 --> 00:37:18.840
Theatrically hug the wretched
and the dispossessed

568
00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:21.240
and cover ourselves in glory
on the front pages?

569
00:37:21.320 --> 00:37:22.480
[Diana] I doubt it.

570
00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:25.400
You barely find it in yourselves
to hug your own.

571
00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:26.680
I hug who I want to.

572
00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:28.760
I hug who I love.

573
00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:32.560
Particularly when they are affected
by the selfishness of others

574
00:37:32.640 --> 00:37:33.480
and need cheering up.

575
00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:35.680
- Who are you referring to?
- Camilla.

576
00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:38.720
Why would I care about her?

577
00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:40.280
[yells] Because I care about her!

578
00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.280
Morning. noon. and night.
I care about her!

579
00:37:46.800 --> 00:37:48.000
And you hurt her.

580
00:37:52.360 --> 00:37:53.600
And if you hurt her…

581
00:37:55.520 --> 00:37:56.520
you hurt me.

582
00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:03.360
Camilla is who I want.

583
00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:06.360
That is where my loyalties lie.

584
00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.800
- That is who my priority is.
- Not the mother of your children?

585
00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:13.280
- Don't bring the boys into this.
- All right. Not the woman you married!

586
00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:17.160
[yells] I refuse to be blamed any longer
for this grotesque misalliance!

587
00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:20.120
I wash my hands of it!

588
00:38:33.840 --> 00:38:35.400
If you have a complaint…

589
00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:38.080
about…

590
00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:40.960
not being loved…

591
00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
or appreciated in this marriage…

592
00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:50.840
I suggest you take it up
with the people who arranged it.

593
00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.320
[doors open and shut]

594
00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:10.960
[water running]

595
00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:38.240
["Baby. It's Cold Outside"
by Ella Fitzgerald playing]

596
00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:47.560
<i>- ♪ I really can't stay ♪
- ♪ But. baby. it's cold outside ♪</i>

597
00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:51.280
<i>- ♪ I've got to go away ♪
- ♪ But. baby. it's cold outside ♪</i>

598
00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:54.600
<i>- ♪ This evening has been ♪
- ♪ Been hoping that you'd drop in ♪</i>

599
00:39:54.680 --> 00:39:56.680
<i>♪ So very nice ♪</i>

600
00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:00.320
<i>♪ I'll hold your hands
They're just like ice ♪</i>

601
00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:04.680
<i>- ♪ My mother will start to worry ♪
- ♪ Beautiful. what's your hurry? ♪</i>

602
00:40:04.760 --> 00:40:08.680
<i>- ♪ And father will be pacing the floor ♪
- ♪ Listen to the fireplace roar ♪</i>

603
00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:13.040
<i>- ♪ So really I'd better scurry ♪
- ♪Beautiful. please don't hurry ♪</i>

604
00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:17.040
<i>- ♪ Well. maybe just a half a drink more ♪
- ♪ Put some records on while I pour ♪</i>

605
00:40:17.120 --> 00:40:21.440
<i>- ♪ The neighbors might think ♪
- ♪ But. baby. it's bad out there ♪</i>

606
00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:25.440
<i>- ♪ Say. what's in this drink? ♪
- ♪ No cabs to be had out there ♪</i>

607
00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:28.320
<i>- ♪ I wish I knew how ♪
- ♪ Your eyes are like starlight now ♪</i>

608
00:40:28.400 --> 00:40:30.120
<i>♪ To break the spell ♪</i>

609
00:40:30.200 --> 00:40:34.040
<i>♪ I'll take your hat
Your hair looks swell ♪</i>

610
00:40:34.120 --> 00:40:38.200
<i>- ♪ I ought to say no. no. no. sir ♪
- ♪ Mind if I move in closer ♪</i>

611
00:40:38.280 --> 00:40:42.480
<i>- ♪ At least I'm gonna say that I tried ♪
- ♪ What's the sense of hurting my pride? ♪</i>

612
00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:45.880
<i>- ♪ I really can't stay ♪
- ♪ Oh. baby. don't hold out. baby ♪</i>

613
00:40:45.960 --> 00:40:49.040
<i>♪ Ah. but it's cold outside… ♪</i>

614
00:40:49.120 --> 00:40:52.440
- [woman] Sir…
- [overlapping chatter]

615
00:40:52.520 --> 00:40:55.280
<i>♪ But. baby. it's cold outside ♪</i>

616
00:40:55.360 --> 00:40:59.400
<i>- ♪ The answer is no ♪
- ♪ But. baby. it's cold outside ♪</i>

617
00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:02.360
<i>- ♪ This welcome has been ♪
- ♪ How lucky that you dropped in ♪</i>

618
00:41:02.440 --> 00:41:04.160
<i>♪ So nice and warm ♪</i>

619
00:41:04.240 --> 00:41:07.920
<i>♪ Look out the window at that storm ♪</i>

620
00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:12.240
<i>- ♪ My sister will be suspicious ♪
- ♪ Gosh. your lips look delicious ♪</i>

621
00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:14.840
<i>- ♪ My brother will be there at the door ♪</i>
- [dogs barking]

622
00:41:14.920 --> 00:41:18.760
<i>- ♪ Waves upon a tropical shore ♪
- ♪ My maiden aunt's mind is vicious ♪</i>

623
00:41:18.840 --> 00:41:21.800
<i>♪ Gosh. your lips are delicious… ♪</i>

624
00:41:21.880 --> 00:41:23.360
[Anne] He is learning. He is.

625
00:41:23.440 --> 00:41:24.720
He's doing much better.

626
00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:26.400
She tells jokes.

627
00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:29.960
but she starts with the punchline.
which sounds funnier than the joke.

628
00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:31.160
[Diana] There you are.

629
00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:33.920
Mama.

630
00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:41.680
Well. I'm sure no one told you.
but I made a request through my office

631
00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:45.400
for us to find a moment
to speak together. in private.

632
00:41:46.600 --> 00:41:48.400
I hope you're not wanting to talk here.

633
00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:50.840
No. not here.

634
00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:52.760
Or now. The dogs need feeding.

635
00:41:52.840 --> 00:41:54.216
- [Diana] The dogs.
- Yes. the dogs.

636
00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:55.760
We'll have to find another time.

637
00:42:04.080 --> 00:42:06.280
- [dogs whimpering]
- [Elizabeth] Who's hungry?

638
00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:07.920
Are you all hungry?

639
00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:10.640
- [barking]
- Who'll tell me about their day?

640
00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:13.120
Hello! Have you had a lovely day?
Have you had fun?

641
00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:23.560
- What are you doing here?
- I hope you don't mind.

642
00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:28.000
- I thought we might find a moment alone.
- Honestly. both of you!

643
00:42:28.520 --> 00:42:29.360
[Charles] Both of us?

644
00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:31.920
You and your wife
ambushing me everywhere I go

645
00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:33.920
with anxious looks. wanting to talk.

646
00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:35.520
I do want to talk. Mummy.

647
00:42:36.760 --> 00:42:37.960
We need to talk.

648
00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:40.400
Fine. Let's talk.

649
00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:43.520
Might I request
we do it like privy counsellors?

650
00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:45.600
On our feet to keep it brief.

651
00:42:52.760 --> 00:42:54.040
It's the marriage.

652
00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:56.520
I had a horrible idea
we were going in this direction.

653
00:42:56.600 --> 00:42:58.120
[Charles] I have done my best.

654
00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:00.840
My very best. and I am suffering!

655
00:43:01.720 --> 00:43:06.000
No. you are not suffering. We're suffering
having to put up with this!

656
00:43:06.080 --> 00:43:08.440
- [grunts]
- Let me make something clear.

657
00:43:08.520 --> 00:43:11.760
When people look at you and Diana.
they see two privileged young people

658
00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:13.040
who. through good fortune.

659
00:43:13.120 --> 00:43:15.480
ended up with everything
one could dream of in life.

660
00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:18.000
No one. not a single breathing.
living soul <i>anywhere.</i>

661
00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:19.240
sees cause for suffering.

662
00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:21.320
- They would if they knew.
- Knew what?

663
00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:24.320
They know that you betray your wife

664
00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:26.160
and make no attempt to hide it.

665
00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:28.760
They know that thanks to you.
she has psychological problems

666
00:43:28.840 --> 00:43:31.800
and eats or doesn't eat
or whatever it is she does or doesn't do.

667
00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:35.960
They know you're a spoiled. immature man.
endlessly complaining unnecessarily.

668
00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:39.440
married to a spoiled. immature woman.
endlessly complaining unnecessarily.

669
00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:41.680
And we are all heartily sick of it.

670
00:43:42.200 --> 00:43:45.240
All anyone wants is for the pair of you
to pull yourselves together.

671
00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:48.280
stop making spectacles of yourselves.
and make this marriage

672
00:43:48.360 --> 00:43:51.160
and your enormously privileged
positions in life work.

673
00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:52.720
And if I want to separate?

674
00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:56.080
You will <i>not </i>separate or divorce
or let the side down in any way.

675
00:43:56.160 --> 00:43:58.440
- And if one day you expect to be king...
- I do.

676
00:43:58.520 --> 00:44:01.120
Then might I suggest
you start to behave like one.

677
00:44:06.520 --> 00:44:08.240
[paper rustling]

678
00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:13.160
[clears throat]

679
00:44:17.240 --> 00:44:19.240
[footsteps receding]

680
00:44:30.400 --> 00:44:32.720
[overlapping chatter and laughter]

681
00:44:40.240 --> 00:44:41.760
- Rabbit. right in the head.
- No!

682
00:45:02.040 --> 00:45:04.040
[choir singing on record]

683
00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:05.360
Have you seen Diana?

684
00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:10.560
[knocking at door]

685
00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:15.760
Come.

686
00:45:19.200 --> 00:45:20.240
[Philip] Hello?

687
00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:22.160
Ah.

688
00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:23.440
Oh. please. no.

689
00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:24.720
[chuckles softly]

690
00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:27.160
I. uh. I came to see if you're all right.

691
00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:35.760
Do you know. I… I don't think
I've ever seen inside this room.

692
00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:38.280
[both chuckle softly]

693
00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:42.200
We can be a rough bunch in this family.

694
00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:46.400
And I'm sure. on occasion.

695
00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:49.120
to a sensitive creature like you.

696
00:45:49.200 --> 00:45:50.280
it must feel like…

697
00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:54.720
Well. let me ask. What does it feel like?

698
00:45:57.520 --> 00:45:59.720
A cold. frozen tundra.

699
00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:02.240
Right.

700
00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:04.680
Like that. then.

701
00:46:05.200 --> 00:46:07.440
An icy. dark.

702
00:46:08.280 --> 00:46:09.880
loveless cave…

703
00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:14.280
with no light…

704
00:46:15.520 --> 00:46:17.800
no hope… anywhere.

705
00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:20.400
Not even the faintest crack.

706
00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:22.120
I see.

707
00:46:25.840 --> 00:46:27.120
He will come around.

708
00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:29.800
He will.

709
00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:31.440
Eventually.

710
00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:33.960
When he realizes that…

711
00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:36.960
he can never have the other one.

712
00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:47.240
Would it help you to realize
we all think he's quite mad?

713
00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:50.520
- [chuckles softly]
- That might have reassured me once.

714
00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:52.840
But I worry we're past that point now.

715
00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:54.640
Sir.

716
00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:58.000
And if he…

717
00:46:58.880 --> 00:47:03.560
If this family can't give me the love
and security that I feel I deserve.

718
00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:05.080
then I believe I have no option

719
00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:08.920
but to break away. officially…
and find it myself.

720
00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.040
- I wouldn't do that if I were you.
- Why not?

721
00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:14.320
Let's just say
I can't see it ending well for you.

722
00:47:14.400 --> 00:47:16.520
[footsteps approaching]

723
00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:18.600
I hope that isn't a threat. sir.

724
00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:21.160
- [knocking]
- No. not now. Out!

725
00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:25.080
[door shuts]

726
00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:36.600
Although we are both outsiders
who married in.

727
00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:39.320
you and I are quite different.

728
00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:42.000
Yes.

729
00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:44.720
I can see that now.

730
00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:51.280
You're right to call me an outsider.

731
00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:55.760
I was an outsider the day that I met the…

732
00:47:57.320 --> 00:48:00.760
the 13-year-old princess
who would one day become my wife.

733
00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:05.520
And after all these years…

734
00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:08.720
I still am.

735
00:48:10.520 --> 00:48:11.520
We all are.

736
00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:14.840
Everyone…

737
00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:16.080
<i>in this system…</i>

738
00:48:17.280 --> 00:48:18.280
<i>is a lost…</i>

739
00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:19.720
<i>lonely…</i>

740
00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:22.840
<i>irrelevant outsider…</i>

741
00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:25.960
<i>apart from the one person.</i>

742
00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:28.440
<i>the only person.</i>

743
00:48:29.120 --> 00:48:30.120
<i>that matters.</i>

744
00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:35.920
<i>She is the oxygen we all breathe.</i>

745
00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:39.200
<i>The essence of all our duty.</i>

746
00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:43.440
Your problem. if I may say…

747
00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:47.560
is you seem to be confused
about who that person is.

748
00:48:52.160 --> 00:48:53.240
[knocking at door]

749
00:48:54.520 --> 00:48:55.520
Come!

750
00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:02.000
Just to say. Your Royal Highnesses.
the photographer is ready.

751
00:49:02.080 --> 00:49:03.080
[Philip] Thank you.

752
00:49:05.560 --> 00:49:06.720
[Philip clears throat]

753
00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:08.640
[children chattering in distance]

754
00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.760
Everyone.
we're going to do the photograph.

755
00:50:19.920 --> 00:50:22.640
Don't you think the Queen
would be best suited in the middle?

756
00:50:22.720 --> 00:50:24.120
[Anne] Charles is pushing in.

757
00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:26.360
You stay outside.

758
00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:27.840
No squabbling. please.

759
00:50:29.920 --> 00:50:32.120
[Charles] Quiet. Quiet.

760
00:50:32.200 --> 00:50:33.880
- Ah. yes.
- [Anne laughing]

761
00:50:33.960 --> 00:50:36.200
[photographer]
The merriest of Christmas smiles!

762
00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:37.160
[Philip] Yes.

763
00:50:37.240 --> 00:50:38.760
[photographer] Three. two. one…

764
00:50:38.840 --> 00:50:40.040
[camera clicks. whirs]

765
00:50:40.120 --> 00:50:41.600
Done. Did anyone blink?

766
00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:42.560
[chuckling]

767
00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:44.640
[indistinct chatter continues]

768
00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:50.800
[choir singing
"Stille Nacht. Heilige Nacht"]

769
00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:55.680
[camera clicks. whirs]

770
00:51:12.160 --> 00:51:16.240
["Stille Nacht. Heilige Nacht" continues]
